Election Policies

This section details the pledges the different political parties make on their official election manifestos, as well as other official party policy on topics.

This section will be updated as manifestos are released.

Conservatives

Brexit

Leave the EU with the current Withdrawal Agreement.

Climate Change

UK will be carbon neutral by 2050.

The building of a nuclear fusion plant to achieve this.

Government will end the sale of new conventional petrol and diesel cars and vans by 2040.

Economy

£100bn investment over five years on road, rail and other infrastructure

Education

From 2022-2023 school year, a new teachers salary will be raised to £30,000.

£7.1bn a year more for schools in England by 2022-23

Business Rates - Taxes on business with properties

Committed to 'reducing the overall burden'.

NHS

2023-2024 budget for NHS England - £140.3bn

£2.7bn for six new hospitals and plans for 34 more

Mental Health

N/A

Police

20,000 new police over 3 years.

£2.5bn on more modern prisons

Extending stop-and-search.

Labour

Brexit

Renegotiate the Withdrawal Agreement to further protect workers and citizen rights, as well as create environmental protections.

This bill will then be put to a public vote, with the choice of Remain or the Withdrawal Agreement

Climate Change

£250bn over 10 years to invest in areas such as clean energy and home insulation

Remove planning restrictions on wind farms

All homes to be zero carbon by 2022.

2000 community buildings will get solar panels.

Economy

Raise minimum wage to £10 for all over-16.

Free broadband for everyone.

A four day workweek.

Tuition fees will be scrapped.

Business Rates - Taxes on business with properties

TV Debates

ITV Debate - 19th November

First TV Debates deal with Brexit, NHS and the monarchy.

On Brexit:

Prime Minister Boris Johnson repeatedly iterated his plan to ‘get Brexit done’.

Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn declined to pick a side but laid out the Labour proposal of a renegotiated Withdrawal Agreement. He feels confident that this can be done in 3 months.

Jeremy Corbyn expressed to PM Johnson that it might take longer than a couple of months to negotiate a free trade agreement with the EU.

On NHS:

Both leaders agreed on the importance of properly funding the NHS.

Jeremy Corbyn claimed that PM Johnson will sell out the NHS to American corporations - this was categorically denied by PM Johnson.

Jeremy Corbyn called for the ‘end of privatisation’.

On the institution of the monarchy:

PM Boris Johnson - ‘the institution of the monarchy is beyond reproach’.

Jeremy Corbyn - ‘it needs a bit of improvement’.

Other topics:

Jeremy Corbyn vouched for a 4 day work week - this idea was ridiculed by the Prime Minister.

Comments:

SNP leader Nicola Sturgeon: ‘not impressed at all’ by the performance of the leaders.

Liberal Democrat leader Jo Swinson: She saw ‘bluster and diversion from both of them’.

A YouGov poll of 1,646 people found that, after you remove the ‘Don’t knows’, 51% of people felt that PM Johnson won the debate.
